HEADWORD: Dory
<hw>Do"ry</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>n.</pos>; <plu><it>pl.</it>
<plw>Dories</plw> <pr>(#)</pr>.</plu> <ety>[Named from 1st color, fr. F.
<ets>dor⟦eacute⟧e</ets> gilded, fr. <ets>dorer</ets> to gild, L.
<ets>deaurare</ets>. See <er>Deaurate</er>, and cf.
<er>Aureole</er>.]</ety> <sn>1.</sn> <fld>(Zool.)</fld> <def>A European
fish. See <er>Doree</er>, and <er>John Doree</er>.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>2.</sn> <fld>(Zool.)</fld> <def>The American wall-eyed perch; --
called also <altname>dor⟦eacute⟧</altname>. See <er>Pike
perch</er>.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Dory</ent>⟦br⟧

